Sure! Below is a simple calculator interface implemented using HTML and JavaScript. This example includes basic arithmetic operations such as addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division.

### HTML Structure
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Calculator</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
        }
        .calculator-container {
            width: 300px;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 8px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
        }
        input[type="text"] {
            width: 100%;
            height: 40px;
            padding: 10px;
            margin-bottom: 15px;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 4px;
            font-size: 20px;
        }
        button {
            width: 100%;
            height: 40px;
            padding: 10px;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 4px;
            font-size: 20px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="calculator-container">
        <input type="text" id="display" readonly>
        <button onclick="appendNumber('7')">7</button>
        <button onclick="appendNumber('8')">8</button>
        <button onclick="appendNumber('9')">9</button>
        <button onclick="appendOperator('+')">+</button>
        <button onclick="clearDisplay()">C</button>
        <button onclick="appendNumber('4')">4</button>
        <button onclick="appendNumber('5')">5</button>
        <button onclick="appendNumber('6')">6</button>
        <button onclick="appendOperator('-')">-</button>
        <button onclick="appendNumber('1')">1</button>
        <button onclick="appendNumber('2')">2</button>
        <button onclick="appendNumber('3')">3</button>
        <button onclick="appendOperator('*')">*</button>
        <button onclick="appendNumber('0')">0</button>
        <button onclick="calculateResult()">=</button>
        <button onclick="appendOperator('/')">/</button>
    </div>

    <script>
        let currentDisplay = '';
        const displayInput = document.getElementById('display');

        function appendNumber(number) {
            currentDisplay += number;
            displayInput.value = currentDisplay;
        }

        function appendOperator(operator) {
            if (currentDisplay === '' || currentDisplay.includes('.')) return;
            displayInput.value += operator;
        }

        function calculateResult() {
            if (currentDisplay === '') return;

            try {
                const result = eval(currentDisplay);
                displayInput.value = result;
                currentDisplay = result.toString();
            } catch (error) {
                displayInput.value = 'Error';
            }
        }

        function clearDisplay() {
            currentDisplay = '';
            displayInput.value = '';
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation
1. **HTML Structure**:
   - A container with a text input for displaying the result and buttons for digits, operators, and basic arithmetic functions.

2. **CSS Styling**:
   - Basic styling to make the calculator look appealing.

3. **JavaScript Logic**:
   - `appendNumber`: Appends numbers to the display.
   - `appendOperator`: Appends operators and handles decimal points.
   - `calculateResult`: Evaluates the expression in the display and updates it.
   - `clearDisplay`: Resets the display.

This calculator can be opened locally in a web browser by saving the HTML file to your computer and opening it with a web server or a local development environment like LiveServer.
